@AdamW, I believe having only the top 20 miners (with 8x H200s or whatever) might create a risk of centralization and reduce competition over time.
It could lead to miners lowering their hardware capacity if they're the only ones left.

A better approach might be to have hundred miners, with a mix of 8x H200s and other types.
This would diversify the network, attract more miners, and help ensure long-term growth and sustainability.

This doesn't apply here, as the minimum hardware requirement to load a 70B model on the base miner is 8 × B200 GPUs. Miners might be able to figure out lower resource requirements while remaining competitive.
Additionally, with DiLoCo, there are diminishing returns as we increase the number of active miners from which we gather gradients. Expanding this number is an active area of research.
I suggest you change the min requirements and add to the incentive mecanism documentation.

Okay, I understand about the minimum hardware requirement.
I have another questions - how could the new miners compete with the existing top 20 miners? With more expensive hardware? With the limited daily incentive, would they invest when the daily income cannot cover the cost of hardware?
If there are no new miners joining, how would you expand the network?
@AdamW ^

We are trying to train a very large model, and this is the only way we can do it.

So far, the model is performing well, which shows that the incentive mechanism is working.

“Fairness,” in the sense of lowering compute requirements, is not the goal of this subnet.

- Team is actively working on research to scale up training participants which would allow faster training/larger models, more participants and lower resources requirements. This is a complex research problem at the frontier of AI research being worked on by multiple teams all over the world. We believe we have an edge in trying to achieve this since we are running the best live unpermissioned decentralized training in the world.
- Our method SparseLoco is already better at allowing smaller participants than other methods operating over the internet, for example the system psyche by nous research has a minimum participation requirement of 64xH100 per contributor, and it is permissioned
- Miners with advanced skills in model parallelism and distributed training can adapt the code to run on lower resources GPUs such as H100 or even alternative hardware such as AMD or TPU

@templar・3 

🌌 **Templar 2.1.0 – The 70B Mega Run Begins** 🌌

The short 70B tests are behind us, and the results were strong. Now it’s time to go big:
we’re launching a **long-term 70B training run** powered by **SparseLoco** and the **Gauntlet incentive mechanism**.

This is the **largest decentralized training run ever attempted** – anywhere. The mission: to see if SparseLoco + Gauntlet can carry us all the way to completion at this scale.

✨ **Highlights:**

* Run versioning: **2.1.0** for the start, with restarts labeled **2.1.1**, **2.1.2**, etc.
* Training will **always restart from checkpoints** – no progress lost.
* Expect continuous updates: more gather peers, new incentives, optimized miners, and other upgrades to cut wall-clock time.

📝 **Tokenizer Upgrade:**

* We’ve switched from **`togethercomputer/LLaMA-2-7B-32K`** (**\~32k vocab, uint16**) → **`google/gemma-3-270m`** (**\~256k vocab, uint32**).
* That’s an **8× increase in vocabulary size**, giving the model more expressive power downstream.
* ⚠️ This means **loss values cannot be compared** to before.
* To keep things consistent across tokenizers, we’re adding **Bits per Byte (BpB)** as the universal metric (and computing it retroactively for older runs). Eventually BpB will replace “loss” as the main number we show.

📦 **Dataset & Shards:**

* With the new tokenizer, the dataset spans **\~1.5 trillion tokens total**.
* Split across **14 shards**, each shard contains about **107 billion tokens (\~100 × 1024³)**.
* Each shard requires **400 GB of storage** on disk (uint32 tokens).
* If data migration fails: just **rclone the first couple of shards** so you can start training. The run will last long enough to **sync the rest gradually** in the background.

🛠 **For Miners and Validators:**

* Follow the instructions in **[`shared_sharded_dataset.md`](https://github.com/tplr-ai/templar/blob/f3165d6f30a7cac8adad68a400a3b53e3eb379ad/docs/shared_sharded_dataset.md)** ([PR #550](https://github.com/tplr-ai/templar/pull/550)).
  * It’s the **same procedure as before**, just updated for the **new shards**.
* Tokenizer changes are in **[PR #580](https://github.com/tplr-ai/templar/pull/580)** (still WIP).
* You must **accept access** to `google/gemma-3-270m` on Hugging Face and save your `HF_TOKEN` in the environment before running.

📊 **Early Training Notes:**

* Downstream evals like HellaSwag will look noisy/unreliable early on. This is expected.
* Checkpoints will be frequent, so don’t worry if there are restarts.

⏰ Kickoff is scheduled for **Friday, September 12, 2025 9:00:00 AM**.

Let’s make history. 🏹

messages.content: @AdamW , Happy to be a miner on #γ・τemplar・3 , Can you please let me know the validation rules and how I can start mining?

Basically you are scored on three metrics (but I would try and dissect the validator code to get a better understanding):

* Gradient score: How much your gradient improves the loss on random data
* Binary indicator: If you have actually trained on the allocated data
* Sync score: How in sync you are with the validators

You can follow these documentations to get started https://github.com/one-covenant/templar/blob/main/docs/miner.md. However it is slightly outdated in parts so just come back if anything is unclear. The minimum required hardware to run base miner is 8xB200.

messages.content: can you explain what this solves ?

Sure. 
Currently, the validator uses multiplicative slashing (score *= 0.75) for miners who don't submit gradients (or not valid gradient out of time window). This creates an infinite decay pattern where scores get progressively smaller (0.75 → 0.5625 → 0.4219...) but mathematically never reach zero. This allows non-contributing miners to maintain tiny positive scores indefinitely. So miners could get free incentive if there is less than 20 positive miners. 
With a configurable threshold act as a floor, this ensures that non-contributing miners are eventually completely removed from scoring consideration rather than hovering at infinitesimally small positive values.
